      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1455">
               <p>Sarah Moore was born at <placeName>King&apos;s Lynn, Norfolk</placeName> in <date
                     when="1738">1738</date>, and moved with her parents to
                     <placeName>Sheffield</placeName> four years later. She began to teach at a
                  school in <placeName>Sheffield</placeName> when seventeen. At eighteen she was
                  appointed the first class-leader at <placeName>Hallam</placeName>, walking there
                  from <placeName>Sheffield</placeName> every week for two years. The first
                  Quarterly Meeting was held in her house at <placeName>Fargate</placeName> between
                     <date when="1756">1756</date> and <date when="1760">1760</date>, and the
                  Society held its meetings there. She married <persName>Samuel Knutton</persName>,
                  a popular local preacher at <placeName>Sheffield</placeName>, in <date when="1772"
                     >1772</date>. See James Everett, <hi rend="italic">Historical Sketches of
                     Wesleyan Methodism, in Sheffield and its Vicinity</hi>
                     (<placeName>Sheffield</placeName>: James Montgomery, <date when="1823"
                     >1823</date>), 1:80.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
